'''Antibody barcoding''' is a [[protein profiling]] technique that has been used to analyze hundreds of proteins from small tissue samples, such as minimally invasive [[fine-needle aspiration|fine-needle aspirates]] from cancer tissue.<ref name=" pmid = 24431113 ">{{cite journal |vauthors=Ullal AV, Peterson V, Agasti SS | title = Cancer cell profiling by barcoding allows multiplexed protein analysis in fine-needle aspirates. | journal = Sci. Transl. Med. | volume = 6 | issue = 219 |date=Jan 2014 | pmid = 24431113 | url = http://stm.sciencemag.org/content/6/218/218ra4.short | pages = 219 | doi=10.1126/scitranslmed.3007361 | pmc=4063286|display-authors=etal}}</ref> Although promising, the technique has not yet been extensively proven or developed.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo/38875/title/Next-Generation--Cancer-Cell-Protein-Profiling/ |title=Next Generation: Cancer Cell Protein Profiling: Antibody barcoding allows scientists and clinicians to analyze protein expression in small amounts of cancer tissue |author=Abby Olena |year=2014 |journal=The Scientist}}</ref>
The method involves [[optical mapping]] of DNA sequences that are added as "barcodes" to [[antibody|antibodies]] attached to the cells in the sample. The method showed high reproducibility and achieved single-cell sensitivity.<ref name=" pmid = 24431113 "/> In addition to profiling cancer cells, the method shows promise as a clinical tool to identify pathway responses to molecularly targeted drugs and to predict drug response in patient samples.<ref name=" pmid = 24431113 "/>
