'''Martin S. Bergmann''' (February 15, 1913 – January 22, 2014) was a clinical professor of psychology of the [[New York University]] post-doctoral program where he taught the course on the history of [[psychoanalysis]]. He was a major voice in the post-Freudian analysis and authored books on human conditions like the Holocaust, the phenomenology of love and child sacrifice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sigourneyaward.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=108&Itemid=67 |title=Martin S. Bergmann, PhD |publisher=Mary S. Sigourney Award Trust |year=1997 |accessdate=2012-03-27}}</ref> 
He was a member of the [[International Psychoanalytical Association]] and an honorary member of the [[American Psychoanalytic Association]].<ref name=PBS>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/youngdrfreud/pages/historians.htm |title=Young Dr. Freud: Featured Historians: Martin S Bergmann |publisher=PBS |year=2002 |accessdate=2012-03-27}}</ref>  In the wake of 9/11 he wrote an article concerning its implications on psychoanalysis called "Psychoanalytical Reflections on September 11, 2001. He was the son of [[Hugo Bergmann]]<ref>[http://www.jewishgen.org/austriaczech/hugo.html The Hugo Bergmann Papers]</ref> and father of [[Michael Bergmann]].

==On film==
Bergmann contributed to the documentaries "[[The Century of the Self]]" (2002)<ref>[http://benatlas.com/2009/11/the-century-of-the-self-by-adam-curtisays-and-the-pr-century/ benatlas.com]</ref> by [[Adam Curtis]]  and ''[[Young Dr. Freud]]''<ref name=PBS/> by [[David Grubin]]. He appeared as Prof. Louis Levy in [[Woody Allen]]'s 1989 feature ''[[Crimes and Misdemeanors]]'',<ref>{{Citation|title=In the Shadow of Moloch|newspaper=[[New York Times Book Review]]|volume=98|year=1993|page=43|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XWwgAQAAMAAJ&q=%22Martin+S.+Bergmann%22+%22Crimes+and+Misdemeanors%22&dq=%22Martin+S.+Bergmann%22+%22Crimes+and+Misdemeanors%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=MM1xT_HiMaLv0gHyw9ncAQ&redir_esc=y|accessdate=2012-03-27}}</ref> and played SS NCO Zablocie in ''[[Schindler's List]]''.<ref>{{IMDb title|0108052|Schindler's List}}</ref>

*''[[Crimes and Misdemeanors]]'' (1989) - Professor Louis Levy
*''[[Schindler's List]]'' (1993) - SS NCO Zablocie

==Death==
Bergmann died on January 22, 2014 aged 100.<ref name="Obituary">{{cite news|last = Fox|first = Margalit|title = Martin S. Bergmann, Psychoanalyst and an On-Screen Philosopher, Dies at 100|newspaper = [[The New York Times]]|page = B7|date = 2014-01-26|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/27/movies/martin-s-bergmann-psychoanalyst-and-woody-allens-on-screen-philosopher-dies-at-100.html?_r=1|accessdate = 2014-02-06}}</ref>

