{{Spanish name 2 |Ramón|Cajal}} {{Infobox person | name = Santiago Ramón y Cajal | image = Cajal-Restored.jpg | birth_date = {{birth date|1852|5|1|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Petilla de Aragón]], [[Navarre]], Spain | death_date = {{death date and age|1934|10|17|1852|5|1|df=y}} | death_place = [[Madrid]], Spain | signature = File:Santiago Ramón y Cajal signature.png | doctoral_students= | known_for = The father of modern Neuroscience | awards = [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]] (1906) }} '''Santiago Ramón y Cajal''' ({{IPA-es|sanˈtjaɣo raˈmon i kaˈxal|lang}}; 1 May 1852 – 17 October 1934) was a Spanish [[neuroscience|neuroscientist]] and [[pathology|pathologist]], specializing in [[neuroanatomy]], particularly the [[histology]] of the [[central nervous system]]. He and [[Camillo Golgi]] received the [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]] in 1906,<ref>https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/medicine/laureates/1906/cajal-bio.html</ref> with Ramón y Cajal thereby becoming the first person of Spanish origin who won a scientific Nobel Prize. His original investigations of the microscopic structure of the brain made him a pioneer of modern [[neuroscience]]. Hundreds of his drawings illustrating the delicate arborizations of brain cells are still in use for educational and training purposes.<ref>{{cite web |title=History of Neuroscience |publisher=Society for Neuroscience |url=http://www.sfn.org/index.cfm?pagename=HistoryofNeuroscience_main |accessdate=2008-10-09 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515121003/http://www.sfn.org/index.cfm?pagename=HistoryofNeuroscience_main |archivedate=2008-05-15 |df= }}</ref>
==Biography== Santiago Ramón y Cajal was born 1 May 1852 in the town of [[Petilla de Aragón]], [[Navarre]], Spain. His father was an anatomy teacher.
As a child he was transferred many times from one school to another because of behavior that was declared poor, rebellious, and showing an anti-[[Authoritarianism|authoritarian]] attitude. An extreme example of his precociousness and rebelliousness at the age of eleven is his 1863 imprisonment for destroying his neighbor's yard gate with a homemade cannon.<ref>Santiago Ramón y Cajal, [http://cvc.cervantes.es/ciencia/cajal/cajal_recuerdos/recuerdos/infancia_10.htm Recuerdos de mi Vida Volume I, Chapter X], Madrid Imprenta y Librería de N. Moya, Madrid 1917, online at Instituto Cervantes (Spanish)</ref>
He was an avid painter, artist, and gymnast, but his father neither appreciated nor encouraged these abilities, even though these artistic talents would contribute to his success later in life. His father apprenticed him to a shoemaker and barber, to "try and give his son much-needed discipline and stability."<ref>{{cite book|title=A Mind for Numbers|publisher=Tarcher Penguin| isbn=978-0-399-16524-5|page=193}}</ref> He was well known for his pugnacious attitude as he worked.{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}
[[File:Ramón y Cajal por Izquierdo Vives 1874 Museo del ejercito Toledo.jpg|thumb|Ramón y Cajal as a young captain in the [[Ten Years' War]] in [[Cuba]], 1874.]]
Over the summer of 1868, his father hoped to interest his son in a medical career, and took him to graveyards to find human remains for anatomical study. Sketching bones was a turning point for him and subsequently, he did pursue studies in medicine.<ref name=Finger2000/>{{rp|207}}
Ramón y Cajal attended the medical school of the [[University of Zaragoza]], where his father was an anatomy teacher. He graduated in 1873, aged 21. After a competitive examination, he served as a medical [[officer (armed forces)|officer]] in the [[Spanish Army]]. He took part in an [[Ten Years' War|expedition to Cuba]] in 1874&ndash;75, where he contracted [[malaria]] and [[tuberculosis]].<ref name=Nobel_lectures>{{cite book|title=Nobel lectures, Physiology or Medicine 1901-1921|year=1967|publisher=Elsevier Publishing Company|location=Amsterdam|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/medicine/laureates/1906/cajal.html|accessdate=2013-01-29}}</ref> In order to heal, he visited the [[Panticosa]] spa-town in the [[Pyrenees]].{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}
After returning to Spain, he received his doctorate in medicine in [[Madrid]] in 1877. In 1879, he became the director of the [[Zaragoza]] Museum, and he married Silveria Fañanás García, with whom he had seven daughters and five sons. Ramón y Cajal worked at the University of Zaragoza until 1883, when he was awarded the position of anatomy professor of the [[University of Valencia]].<ref name=Nobel_lectures/> His early work at these two universities focused on the pathology of [[inflammation]], the microbiology of [[cholera]], and the structure of [[Epithelium|epithelial]] cells and tissues.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}
In 1887 Ramón y Cajal moved to [[Barcelona]] for a professorship.<ref name=Nobel_lectures/> There he first learned about [[Golgi's method]], a cell staining method which uses potassium dichromate and silver nitrate to (randomly) stain a few neurons a dark black color, while leaving the surrounding cells transparent. This method, which he improved, was central to his work, allowing him to turn his attention to the [[central nervous system]] (brain and spinal cord), in which neurons are so densely intertwined that standard microscopic inspection would be nearly impossible. During this period he made extensive detailed drawings of neural material, covering many species and most major regions of the brain.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}
In 1892, he became professor at [[Madrid]].<ref name=Nobel_lectures/> in 1899 he became director of the ''Instituto Nacional de Higiene &ndash; ''translated as ''National Institute of Hygiene '', and in 1922 founder of the {{lang|es|Laboratorio de Investigaciones Biológicas}} &ndash; translated as the ''Laboratory of Biological Investigations '', later renamed to the {{lang|es|Instituto Cajal}}, or [[Cajal Institute]].<ref name=Nobel_lectures/>
He died in Madrid on October 17, 1934, at the age of 82,<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Sherrington | first1 = C. S. | title = Santiago Ramón y Cajal. 1852-1934 | doi = 10.1098/rsbm.1935.0007 | journal = Obituary Notices of Fellows of the Royal Society | volume = 1 | issue = 4 | pages = 424–441 | year = 1935 | pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> continuing to work even on his deathbed.<ref name=Nobel_lectures/><ref>{{cite journal|last=Yuste|first=Rafael|title=The discovery of dendritic spines by Ramón y Cajal|date=21 April 2015|journal=Frontiers in Neuroanatomy|volume=9|issue=18|pmc=4404913|doi=10.3389/fnana.2015.00018|pmid=25954162}}</ref>
===Political and religious views=== In 1877, the 25-year-old Ramón y Cajal joined a [[Masonic lodge]].<ref name=pin/>{{rp|156}} John Brande Trend wrote in 1965 that Ramón y Cajal "was a liberal in politics, an evolutionist in philosophy, an agnostic in religion".<ref>{{cite book|title=The Origins of Modern Spain|year=1965|publisher=Russell & Russell|author=John Brande Trend|page=82|quote=Ramón y Cajal was a liberal in politics, an evolutionist in philosophy, an agnostic in religion...}}</ref>
Nonetheless, Ramón y Cajal used the term soul "without any shame".<ref>{{cite book|title=Educating the Whole Child for the Whole World: The Ross School Model and Education for the Global Era|year=2010|publisher=NYU Press| isbn=9780814741405| author=Carolyn Sattin-Bajaj|editor=Marcelo Suarez-Orozco|page=165|quote=In that sense, it was interesting to learn that Santiago Ramón y Cajal, the great pioneer of modern neuroanatomy, was agnostic, but still used the term soul without any shame.}}</ref> He was said to later have regretted having left organized religion,<ref name=pin>José María López Piñero, "Santiago Ramón y Cajal", Universita de València</ref>{{rp| 343}} Ultimately, he became convinced of a belief in God as a creator, as stated during his first lecture before the [[Spanish Royal Academy of Sciences]].<ref>[http://www.rac.es/ficheros/doc/00207.pdf DISCURSO DEL SR. D. SANTIAGO RAMÓN Y CAJALTEMA: FUNDAMENTOS RACIONALES Y CONDICIONES TÉCNICAS DE LAINVESTIGACIÓN BIOLÓGICA] Sesquicentenario de Santiago Ramon y Cajal], 23 pages, p. 39-40: ''a los que te dicen que la Ciencia apaga toda poesía, secando las fuentes del sentimiento y el ansia de misterio que late en el fondo del alma humana, contéstales que á la vana poesía del vulgo, basada en una noción errónea del Universo, noción tan mezquina como pueril, tú sustituyes otra mucho más grandiosa y sublime, que es la poesía de la verdad, la incomparable belleza de la obra de Dios y de las leyes eternas por Él establecidas. Él acierta exclusivamente a comprender algo de ese lenguaje misterioso que Dios ha escrito en los fenómenos de la Naturaleza; y a él solamente le ha sido dado desentrañar la maravillosa obra de la Creación para rendir a la Divinidad uno de los cultos más gratos y aceptos a un Supremo entendimiento, el de estudiar sus portentosas obras, para en ellas y por ellas conocerle, admirarle y reverenciarle.'' [English Translation: P. 39-40: To those who tell you that Science quenches all poetry, drying up the sources of feeling and the longing for mystery that pulses in the depths of the human soul, tell them that in the vain poetry of the people, based on an erroneous notion of Universe, as petty as it is puerile, you substitute a much more grandiose and sublime one, which is the poetry of truth, the incomparable beauty of the work of God and the eternal laws established by him. He is only able to understand something of that mysterious language that God has written in the phenomena of Nature; And he has only been able to unravel the wonderful work of Creation to render to the Divinity one of the most grateful and accepted cults to a supreme understanding, to study his portentous works, for them and for them to know, to admire and to revere him ]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.serrablo.org/revista/151/las-creencias-de-darwin-y-cajal |title=Las creencias de Darwin y Cajal &#124; Amigos de Serrablo |publisher=Serrablo.org |date=2009-03-31 |accessdate=2015-03-15}}</ref>
==Discoveries and theories== [[File:Cajal-mi.jpg|thumb|right|Ramón y Cajal in his laboratory.]]
Ramón y Cajal made several major contributions to neuroanatomy.<ref name=Finger2000>{{cite book|last=Finger|first=Stanley|title=Minds behind the brain: A history of the pioneers and their discoveries.|date=2000|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=0-19-508571-X|pages=197–216|chapter=Chapter 13: Santiago Ramón y Cajal. From nerve nets to neuron doctrine}}</ref> He discovered the axonal [[growth cone]], and demonstrated experimentally that the relationship between nerve cells was not ''continuous'', but ''contiguous''.<ref name=Finger2000 /> This provided definitive evidence for what [[Heinrich Wilhelm Gottfried von Waldeyer-Hartz|Heinrich Waldeyer]] coined the term [[neuron theory]] as opposed to the [[reticular theory]] This is now widely considered the foundation of modern neuroscience.<ref name=Finger2000 />
He was an advocate of the existence of [[dendritic spines]], although he did not recognize them as the site of contact from presynaptic cells. He was a proponent of polarization of nerve cell function and his student, [[Rafael Lorente de Nó]], would continue this study of input-output systems into [[cable theory]] and some of the earliest circuit analysis of neural structures.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}
By producing excellent depictions of neural structures and their connectivity and providing detailed descriptions of cell types he discovered a new type of cell, which was subsequently named after him, the [[interstitial cell of Cajal]] (ICC).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anaesthetist.com/anaes/patient/ans/Findex.htm#ens.htm |title=FANZCA part I notes on the Autonomic Nervous System |publisher=Anaesthetist.com |date= |accessdate=2015-03-15}}</ref> This cell is found interleaved among neurons embedded within the [[smooth muscle tissue|smooth muscles]] lining the [[Gastrointestinal tract|gut]], serving as the generator and pacemaker of the [[catastalsis|slow waves of contraction]] which move [[chyme|material]] along the [[gastrointestinal tract]], mediating neurotransmission from motor neurons to smooth muscle cells.
In his 1894 [[Croonian Lecture]], Ramón y Cajal suggested (in an extended metaphor) that cortical [[pyramidal cells]] may become more elaborate with time, as a tree grows and extends its branches.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}
He devoted a considerable amount of time studying French which he used to help his wife during labor and parapsychological phenomena.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} A book he had written on these topics was lost during the [[Spanish Civil War]].{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}
Ramón y Cajal's efforts to improve the state of scientific research and education in Spain were part of a broader preoccupation with [[Regenerationism]] among Spanish intellectuals.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}
==Distinctions== [[File:Ramón y Cajal Burgos.JPG|thumb|right|Bust of Santiago Ramón y Cajal in [[Burgos]].]]
Ramón y Cajal received many prizes, distinctions, and societal memberships during his scientific career, including [[honorary degree|honorary doctorates in medicine]] from [[Cambridge University]] and [[Würzburg University]] and an honorary [[Doctor of Philosophy|doctorate in philosophy]] from [[Clark University]].<ref name=Nobel_lectures/> The most famous distinction he was awarded was the [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]] in 1906, together with the Italian scientist [[Camillo Golgi]] "in recognition of their work on the structure of the nervous system".<ref name=Nobel_lectures/> This caused some controversy because Golgi, a staunch supporter of [[reticular theory]], disagreed with Ramón y Cajal in his view of the neuron doctrine.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} Even before Ramón y Cajal's work, Norwegian scientist [[Fridtjof Nansen]] established the contiguous nature of nerve cells in his study of certain marine life, which Ramón y Cajal failed to cite.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = [[J. S. Edwards]] & [[R. Huntford]] | title = Fridtjof Nansen: from the neuron to the North Polar Sea | journal = [[Endeavour (journal)|Endeavour]] | volume = 22 | issue = 2 | pages = 76–80 | year = 1998 | month = | pmid = 9719772 }}</ref>
==Publications== He published more than 100 scientific works and articles in Spanish, [[French language|French]] and [[German language|German]]. Among his most notable works were:<ref name=Nobel_lectures/> * ''Rules and advice on scientific investigation'' * ''Histology'' * ''Degeneration and regeneration of the nervous system'' * ''Manual of normal histology and micrographic technique'' * ''Elements of histology''
A list of his books includes: *{{cite book| author = Ramón y Cajal, Santiago | orig-year = 1890 |date=1905 |edition=fourth | title = Manual de Anatomia Patológica General (Handbook of general Anatomical Pathology) | language = Spanish | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=EK9jSth-buQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Manual+de+Anatomia+Patologica+General+cajal#v=onepage&q&f=false }} *{{cite book| author = Ramón y Cajal, Santiago |author2=Richard Greeff | year = 1894 | publisher = Bergmann | title = Die Retina der Wirbelthiere: Untersuchungen mit der Golgi-cajal'schen Chromsilbermethode und der ehrlich'schen Methylenblaufärbung (Retina of vertebrates) | language = German | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=rSXltRD9VDsC }} *{{cite book| author = Ramón y Cajal, Santiago |author2=L. Azoulay | year = 1894 | publisher = C. Reinwald | title = Les nouvelles idées sur la structure du système nerveux chez l'homme et chez les vertébrés' ('New ideas on the fine anatomy of the nerve centres''). | language = French | url = https://archive.org/details/lesnouvellesid00ram }} *{{cite book| author = Ramón y Cajal, Santiago |author2=Johannes Bresler |author3=E. Mendel | year = 1896 | publisher = Verlag von Johann Ambrosius Barth | title = Beitrag zum Studium der Medulla Oblongata: Des Kleinhirns und des Ursprungs der Gehirnnerven | language = German | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=lFDQWR8dPucC }} *{{cite journal|last=Ramón y Cajal |first=Santiago |title=Estructura del quiasma óptico y teoría general de los entrecruzamientos de las vías nerviosas. (Structure of the Chiasma opticum and general theory of the crossing of nerve tracks) |journal=Rev. Trim. Micrográfica |year=1898 |volume=3 |pages=15–65 |trans-title= Die Structur des Chiasma opticum nebst einer allgemeine Theorie der Kreuzung der Nervenbahnen (German, 1899, Verlag Joh. A. Barth) |language=Spanish}} *{{cite book| author = Ramón y Cajal, Santiago | year = 1899 | title = Comparative study of the sensory areas of the human cortex | url= https://books.google.com/books?id=2Dv-zWg89tsC&oe=UTF-8 | archive-url = https://archive.org/details/comparativestud00cajagoog |archive-date=10 September 2009 | pages= 85 |language=English}} *{{cite book| author = Ramón y Cajal, Santiago | year = 1899–1904 | publisher = Madrid | title = Textura del sistema nervioso del hombre y los vertebrados. | language = Spanish | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=TOXPYTEz4pkC&printsec=frontcover&dq=editions:26P2Bq9bIxkC&hl=es&sa=X&ei=2Yf0U4PHHeGy7AbCt4AQ&ved=0CCAQ6wEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false }} **{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/histologiedusyst01ram |title=Histologie du système nerveux de l'homme & des vertébrés |last=Ramón y Cajal |first=Santiago |author-mask=2 |via=Internet Archive |date= |language=French}} **{{cite book |last=Ramón y Cajal |first=Santiago |author-mask=2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DMETOdFiJwMC&printsec=frontcover&hl=es&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Texture of the Nervous System of Man and the Vertebrates }} *{{cite book| author = Ramón y Cajal, Santiago | year = 1906 | publisher = Johann Ambrosius Barth | title = Studien über die Hirnrinde des Menschen v.5 (Studies about the meninges of man) | language = German | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=eMmtxDaSFv8C }} *{{cite book| author = Ramón y Cajal, Santiago | others = Translated by Neely Swanson and Larry W. Swanson | year = 1999 | origyear = 1897 | title = Advice for a Young Investigator | publisher = [[MIT Press]] | location = Cambridge | isbn = 0-262-68150-1 }} *{{cite book| author = Ramón y Cajal, Santiago | year = 1937 | title = Recuerdos de mi Vida |language=es| publisher = [[MIT Press]] | location = Cambridge | isbn = 84-206-2290-7 }} In 1905, he published five science-fiction stories called "Vacation Stories" under the pen name "Dr. Bacteria".<ref>http://www.lablit.com/article/226/</ref>{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}
==In society and culture== The asteroid [[117413 Ramonycajal]] has been named in his honor.
In 2014, the [[National Institutes of Health]] exhibited original Ramón y Cajal drawings in its Neuroscience Research Center.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QIDUKHXqtg4 NIH Exhibits Original Cajal Neuroscience Drawings] Intramural Research Program at the National Institutes of Health (NIH IRP), YouTube, 2:16 min</ref>
An exhibition called ''The Beautiful Brain: The Drawings of Santiago Ramón y Cajal'' travelled through the US beginning 2017 at the [[Weisman Art Museum]] in Minneapolis ending April 2019 at the [[Ackland Art Museum]] in Chapel Hill, North Carolina.<ref>[http://wam.umn.edu/calendar/cajal/The Beautiful Brain: The Drawings of Santiago Ramón y Cajal ] The Weisman Art Museum, retrieved 9 August 2017</ref>
A short documentary by REDES is available on YouTube<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bpUZcAStXkY Documental sobre Santiago Ramón y Cajal en Redes] YouTube, 34 min, Sep 22, 2012. (Spanish)</ref> Spanish public television filmed a biopic series to commemorate his life.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}
